{"title_page": "Bondi Rescue", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Bondi Rescue\n| image                    = Bondi Rescue logo.png\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = Factual\n| creator                  = Ben Davies\n| based_on                 = <!-- {{based on|work|author}} -->\n| developer                = \n| writer                   = \n| screenplay               = \n| story                    = \n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist|\n* Anthony \"Harries\" Carroll\n}}\n| starring                 = The Waverley Council Lifeguards\n| judges                   = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = [[Osher G\u00fcnsberg]]\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \"[[In the Summertime (Thirsty Merc song)|In the Summertime]]\" by [[Thirsty Merc]]\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = Australia\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 15\n| num_episodes             = 176 <!--- (as of 8 April 2020) --->\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = Michael Cordell<br />Nick Murray\n| producer                 = Martin Baker<br />Nia Pericles<br />Mark Hooper<br />Nick Robinson<br />Rachale Davies<br />Liam Taylor<br />Madeleine Hetherton<br />Romy Page<br />Warwick Burton\n| editor                   = \n| location                 = [[Bondi Beach]], [[New South Wales]]\n| cinematography           = Gary Russell<br />Phillip Bull<br />Helen Patronis\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 30 \u2013 60 minutes ''(Including commercials)''\n| company                  = Cordell Jigsaw Productions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjz.com.au |title=CJZ.com.au |accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor              = \n| budget                   = \n| channel                  = [[Network 10]]\n| picture_format           = 576i (SDTV)<br />1080i (HDTV)\n| audio_format             = Stereo\n| first_run                = <!-- The nation in which the series first aired, if different from country parameter. -->\n| released                 = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| first_aired              = 15 February 2006\n| last_aired               = Present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = ''[[Bondi Vet]]''\n| website                  = http://www.bondirescue.com.au\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = https://www.cjz.com.au/programs/bondi-rescue/\n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''Bondi Rescue''''' is an Australian factual television program which is broadcast on [[Network 10]]. The program, which has aired since 2006, follows the daily lives and routines of the [[Waverley Council]] professional lifeguards who patrol [[Bondi Beach]].<ref>[http://www.waverley.nsw.gov.au/things_to_do/beaches_and_the_coast/lifeguards Waverley Council - Professional Lifeguards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322080308/http://www.waverley.nsw.gov.au/things_to_do/beaches_and_the_coast/lifeguards |date=22 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n''Bondi Rescue'' was first broadcast in 2006. A spin-off, set in [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]], also briefly screened in 2008.<ref name=TVT2/><ref>{{cite news|title=Not drowning, saving|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/09/17/1221330909490.html|publisher=[[The Age]]|date=18 September 2008}}</ref> ''Bondi Rescue'' is also broadcast internationally throughout 100 countries.\n\nThe show was created and produced by part-time lifeguard Ben Davies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/tv--radio/much-kuta-than-here/2008/09/06/1220121584411.html|title=Much Kuta than here|date=8 September 2008|last=Forbes|first=Mark|accessdate=18 July 2011|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]}}</ref> It is narrated by [[Osher G\u00fcnsberg]].\n\n[[File:Bondi rescue lifeguard - Paris hilton bondi beach 31 december 2008 (7).jpg|thumb|Dunstan \"Dunno\" Foss (black cap) and [[Ryan Clark (actor)|Ryan \"Whippet\" Clark]] (white cap) with [[Paris Hilton]] on Bondi Beach on New Year's Eve 2008]]\n\n==Overview==\nThe Bondi lifeguards perform around five thousand rescues over the summer period. They also deal with other incidents including lost children, shark scares, [[Portuguese man o' war|bluebottle]] stings, injuries, sexual deviants, drunk beach goers and thieves on the beach. Every once in a while, celebrities also make appearances on their shores. These have included actors/comedians [[David Hasselhoff]] and [[Kelly Slater]] (stars of the US lifeguards fiction show Baywatch), [[Hugh Grant]], [[Zac Efron]], [[Rowan Atkinson]], [[Paris Hilton]], [[Russell Crowe]], entrepreneur [[Richard Branson]], American comedian [[Conan O'Brien]], musician [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Steve Irwin]] and daughter [[Bindi Irwin|Bindi]] and the [[India national cricket team|Indian Cricket Team]]. Bondi veterinarian [[Chris Brown (veterinarian)|Chris Brown]] repeatedly appeared on Bondi beach, meeting lifeguards, in his own show [[Bondi Vet]].\n\nBondi also has its Annual Lifeguard [[Ironman (surf lifesaving)|Ironman]] Challenge, which tests the skills of each lifeguard with a one-kilometre run from Bondi to local beach [[Tamarama]], then a one-kilometre swim to nearby [[Bronte Beach]], followed by a two-kilometre board-paddle back to Bondi. The race is  handicapped: the more accomplished swimmers and board-paddlers set off from Bondi later (up to twelve minutes, depending on how many competitors there are).\n\nFootage for the show is shot during the preceding Australian summer (usually between November and February), with certain episodes reflecting incidents that have occurred during Christmas Day, New Year's Day and [[Australia Day]]. Noteworthy incidents at nearby Tamarama and Bronte Beaches, which the lifeguards are also responsible for, are occasionally shown. Later seasons also featured footage of lifeguard trials and training exercises from the middle of the year. The training in the middle of the year is a trial to test the fitness, strength and ability of the lifeguards. It consists of an 800-metre swim in under thirteen-and-a-half minutes in a swimming pool, then a 600-metre swim surf and two 600-metre runs and on the sand and also a 600-metre board paddle then a set of demanding rescues at Bondi which should be completed in under 25 minutes. It is also a test for trainee lifeguards to show they are able and committed to the role of a lifeguard. If the competitors do not complete the tasks in the time limit, they are eliminated and do not advance to the next test.\n\nMany rescue boards and jet skis have a camera attached for close-up footage. When deemed safe to do so, the cameraman accompanies the lifeguards out to sea and has even had to assist with rescue operations on a number of occasions.\n\nThe production company pays [[Waverley Council]] $139,000 per year and a percentage of profits to film the program, and the Council also holds \"review rights\" to ensure content is acceptable to their practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2016/03/139k-to-film-at-bondi-rescue.html|title=$139k to film at Bondi Rescue |date=15 March 2016|accessdate=15 March 2016|work=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox}}</ref>\n\n==The lifeguards==\n'''Current lifeguards at Bondi beach'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://10play.com.au/bondi-rescue/lifeguards/season-15|title=Bondi Rescue \u2014 Lifeguards|date=26 March 2020|website=[[10 Play (Network Ten)|10 Play]]|publisher=[[Network Ten]]|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*Aaron \"Azza\"/\"Azza B\" Buchan \u2014 Featu