{"title_page": "Ashford to Ramsgate line", "text_new": "{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Ashford to Ramsgate line\n|box_width   = \n|color       =\n|logo        =\n|logo_width  =\n|image       = Wye station (Class 411 1619) 01.JPG\n|image_width = 300px\n|caption     = Class 411 1619 with a 4-car set in Jaffa Cake livery leaves Wye station in 1989\n|type        = [[Heavy rail]]\n|system      = [[National Rail]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = [[Kent]],<br>[[South East England]]\n|start       = \n|end         = \n|stations    = 11\n|routes      =\n|daily_ridership =\n|open        = \n|close       =\n|owner       = [[Network Rail]] \n|operator    = [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]\n|character   =\n|depot       = \n|stock       = {{BRC|375}} \"[[Electrostar]]\", {{BRC|395}} \"[[Javelin]]\" \n|linelength  =\n|tracklength =\n|tracks      = 2\n|gauge       = {{track gauge|uksg|allk=on}}\n|electrification = \n|speed       = \n|elevation   =\n|map         = [[File:Kent Railways.svg|250px|The Ashford to Ramsgate line,<br> shown with other railway lines in Kent]]\n{{Ashford to Ramsgate (via Canterbury West) line|inline=1}}\n|map_state   = collapsed\n}}\n\nThe '''Ashford to Ramsgate line''' is a railway that runs through [[Kent]] from [[Ashford International railway station|Ashford]] to [[Ramsgate railway station|Ramsgate]] via [[Canterbury West railway station|Canterbury West]]. Its route parallels the coastal [[South Eastern main line]] and [[Kent Coast line]] route that runs between the same places via [[Dover Priory railway station|Dover]].\n\nThe line was opened in 1846 by the [[South Eastern Railway (UK)|South Eastern Railway]] (SER), who wanted to compete with rival railway companies, particularly the [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] (LDCR) for traffic between London and Thanet. The SER's route included reversing at Ramsgate to take a branch line to {{rws|Margate Sands}}; this line has since closed. The remainder of the line is double-track and [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|electrified]] with 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[third rail]]. At Ashford it links to [[High Speed 1]] for fast services to {{rws|St Pancras International}}.\n\n==Services==\nServices are operated by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]. {{As of|2019|12}}, the typical off-peak down service per hour is:\n\n* One high-speed service from [[St Pancras railway station|London St. Pancras International]] towards {{stnlnk|Margate}}, stopping only at {{stnlnk|Canterbury West}}\n* One service from [[Charing Cross railway station|Charing Cross]] to {{stnlnk|Ramsgate}}, stopping at {{stnlnk|Wye}}, Canterbury West, {{stnlnk|Sturry}} and {{stnlnk|Minster}} and skipping {{stnlnk|Chilham}} and {{stnlnk|Chartham}}\n* One service from London Victoria via {{stnlnk|Maidstone East}} to Canterbury West only, stopping at Wye, Chilham and Chartham\nA small number of peak services on the [[Kent Coast line]] run onto the Ashford to Ramsgate line at Minster and then reverse as a school service, running Ramsgate-Minster-Sandwich-Deal (mornings) or the reverse (evenings).<ref> [https://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/-/media/goahead/southeastern/documents/timetables/december-timetable/december-timetable-1---15-december---16-may.pdf] Southeastern December 2019: London - Ashford, Folkestone, Dover and Margate </ref>\n\n==History==\nThe line was proposed by the [[South Eastern Railway (UK)|South Eastern Railway]] (SER) as a branch from its [[South Eastern Main Line|main line]] in April 1834. At the time, coastal towns on the [[Isle of Thanet]] such as [[Margate]] and [[Ramsgate]] were undergoing a rise in popularity as holiday resorts, and railways could be seen as faster and cheaper rivals to the [[steamboat]] traffic bringing holidaymakers from London. However, the SER suffered from having no direct access to Thanet on their network except via Ashford. By August 1836, the rival [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] (LCDR) made its own proposal to serve Thanet.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=243}} Planning for the line stalled for a while, but by 1840 the SER realised that rival railways were making serious proposals for lines to Thanet.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=244}} After the LCDR's line reached Dover on 22 July 1861, there was serious competition between the two companies for continental port traffic.{{sfn|Grant|2017|p=520}}\n\nConstruction on the line began in September 1884. The SER were not convinced the railway would be a success, and so built it as single track, with space to add an additional track if necessary, and crossed roads at level in several places, including [[Wye, Kent|Wye]], [[Chartham]] and [[Sturry]]. The line ran through [[Minster-in-Thanet|Minster]] to Ramsgate, then doubled back on a branch line to {{rws|Margate Sands}}, which required trains reversing. The overall planned cost was \u00a3385,339.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=244}}\n\nThe line opened as far as Canterbury on 6 February 1846.{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=53}} Intermediate stations were not immediately provided, but opened soon afterwards; [[Wye railway station]] was open by April 1846. A station was planned at [[Godmersham]] but then cancelled. The extension to Ramsgate opened on 13 April, with stations at {{rws|Grove Ferry}}, Minster and Ramsgate. The SER hoped by building the line to Ramsgate, it would be able to run [[boat train]] services to [[Ostend]].{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=245}} The Margate branch was delayed and finally opened on 1 December 1846.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=246}} An intermediate station at Sturry opened on 22 April 1847.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=246}}\n\nThe goods and cattle facilities at Ramsgate made the line popular for transporting these, and they were extended in 1895. An additional siding was added at Wye in 1895 to serve racing traffic.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=251}}\n\nThe rivalry between the SER and LDCR almost bankrupted both companies, and consequently they formed a joined management committee, known as the [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]] (SECR), in 1899.{{sfn|Grant|2017|p=520}} This then became part of the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]] (SR) as part of the grouping under the [[Railways Act 1921]]. In 1924, a {{convert|1.5|miles|adj=on}} extension began construction between the former SER line at Ramsgate and the former LCDR line at {{rws|Dumpton Park}}. This opened on 2 July 1926. At the same time, the former SER branch to Margate Sands closed to passengers, as did the stations at {{rws|Ramsgate Town}} and {{rws|Ramsgate Harbour}}. The Margate Sands branch line survived as a goods depot until November 1976, when it was closed completely.{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2007|p=52-53,66}}\n\nThe line was electrified in 1961 under the [[British Railways|BR]] [[1955 Modernisation Plan]].{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2007|p=53}} Grove Ferry station closed on 3 January 1966.{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2007|p=123}}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\nOn 11 August 1858, an excursion train was derailed near {{rws|Chilham}}. Three people were killed.<ref name=Kidner>{{cite book | first = R. W.| last = Kidner| year = 1977 |origyear=1963 | title = The South Eastern and Chatham Railway | publisher = The Oakwood Press| location = Tarrant Hinton | isbn = | page=48 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 January 1877, a major storm hit Kent, causing damage along the line. The roof at Canterbury West was damaged, and a timber bridge across the line blew down. The bridge was replaced three months later by a subway.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=250}}\n\nOn 9 October 1894, an early morning goods train carrying hop pickers from Ashford to Canterbury West collided with a horse and cart on a level crossing close to Horton Chapel Farm. Five people were killed immediately, and two later died from their injuries. The SER denied responsibility and blamed the cart driver who did not check to see if a train was coming.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=251}}\n\nOn 15 July 1970, an [[electric multiple unit]] was in collision with a [[lorry]] on an [[level crossing|occupation crossing]] between {{rws|Chartham}} and Chilham due to an error by the crossing keeper. The driver of the lorry and the guard of the train were killed.<ref name=Glover>{{cite book |title=Southern Electric |first=John |last=Glover |publisher=Ian Allan |location=Hersham |year=2001 |page=142 |isbn=0 7110 2807 9}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2015, electric multiple unit [[British Rail Class 375|375 703]] was in collision with a herd of [[cattle]] on the line at Chilham and was derailed. There were no injuries amongst the 70 passengers.<ref name=BBC33671351>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-33671351 |title=Train derailed after hitting cows on line in Kent |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=KO40716>{{cite web |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/ashford/news/train-derailed-after-hitting-cattle-40716/ |title=Southeastern Train travelling between Chilham and Wye derails after hitting cattle |publisher=Kent Messenger Group |work=Kent Online |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> The line was closed until 30 July.<ref name=BBC33692912>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-33692912 |title=Kent line closed by cows-on-line derailment to reopen |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{butt-stations}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grant|first=Donald|title=Directory of the Railway Companies of Great Britain|publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd|year=2017|isbn=978-1-788-03768-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gray|first=Adrian|title=South Eastern Railway|publisher=Middleton Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0-906520-85-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Colin|last2=McCarthy|first2=David|title=Railway of Britain : Kent and Sussex|publisher=Ian Allan|year=2007|isbn=978-0-7110-3222-4|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Commons category|Ashford to Ramsgate (via Canterbury West) Line}}\n{{Railway lines in South East England|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ashford To Ramsgate (Via Canterbury West) Line}}\n[[Category:Rail transport in Kent]]\n[[Category:Transport in Ashford, Kent]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in South East England]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Ashford to Ramsgate line\n|box_width   = \n|color       =\n|logo        =\n|logo_width  =\n|image       = Wye station (Class 411 1619) 01.JPG\n|image_width = 300px\n|caption     = Class 411 1619 with a 4-car set in Jaffa Cake livery leaves Wye station in 1989\n|type        = [[Heavy rail]]\n|system      = [[National Rail]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = [[Kent]],<br>[[South East England]]\n|start       = \n|end         = \n|stations    = 11\n|routes      =\n|daily_ridership =\n|open        = \n|close       =\n|owner       = [[Network Rail]] \n|operator    = [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]\n|character   =\n|depot       = \n|stock       = {{BRC|375}} \"[[Electrostar]]\", {{BRC|395}} \"[[Javelin]]\" \n|linelength  =\n|tracklength =\n|tracks      = 2\n|gauge       = {{track gauge|uksg|allk=on}}\n|electrification = \n|speed       = \n|elevation   =\n|map         = [[File:Kent Railways.svg|250px|The Ashford to Ramsgate line,<br> shown with other railway lines in Kent]]\n{{Ashford to Ramsgate (via Canterbury West) line|inline=1}}\n|map_state   = collapsed\n}}\n\nThe '''Ashford to Ramsgate line''' is a railway that runs through [[Kent]] from [[Ashford International railway station|Ashford]] to [[Ramsgate railway station|Ramsgate]] via [[Canterbury West railway station|Canterbury West]]. Its route parallels the coastal [[South Eastern main line]] and [[Kent Coast line]] route that runs between the same places via [[Dover Priory railway station|Dover]].\n\nThe line was opened in 1846 by the [[South Eastern Railway (UK)|South Eastern Railway]] (SER), who wanted to compete with rival railway companies, particularly the [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] (LDCR) for traffic between London and Thanet. The SER's route included reversing at Ramsgate to take a branch line to {{rws|Margate Sands}}; this line has since closed. The remainder of the line is double-track and [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|electrified]] with 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[third rail]]. At Ashford it links to [[High Speed 1]] for fast services to {{rws|St Pancras International}}.\n\n==Services==\nServices are operated by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]]. {{As of|2019|12}}, the typical off-peak down service per hour is:\n\n* One high-speed service from [[St Pancras railway station|London St. Pancras International]] towards {{stnlnk|Margate}}, stopping only at {{stnlnk|Canterbury West}}\n* One service from [[Charing Cross railway station|Charing Cross]] to {{stnlnk|Ramsgate}}, stopping at {{stnlnk|Wye}}, Canterbury West, {{stnlnk|Sturry}} and {{stnlnk|Minster}} and skipping {{stnlnk|Chilham}} and {{stnlnk|Chartham}}\n* One service from London Victoria via {{stnlnk|Maidstone East}} to Canterbury West only, stopping at Wye, Chilham and Chartham\nA small number of peak services on the [[Kent Coast line]] run onto the Ashford to Ramsgate line at Minster and then reverse as a school service, running Ramsgate-Minster-Sandwich-Deal (mornings) or the reverse (evenings).<ref> [https://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/-/media/goahead/southeastern/documents/timetables/december-timetable/december-timetable-1---15-december---16-may.pdf] Southeastern December 2019: London - Ashford, Folkestone, Dover and Margate </ref>\n\n==History==\nThe line was proposed by the [[South Eastern Railway (UK)|South Eastern Railway]] (SER) as a branch from its [[South Eastern Main Line|main line]] in April 1834. At the time, coastal towns on the [[Isle of Thanet]] such as [[Margate]] and [[Ramsgate]] were undergoing a rise in popularity as holiday resorts, and railways could be seen as faster and cheaper rivals to the [[steamboat]] traffic bringing holidaymakers from London. However, the SER suffered from having no direct access to Thanet on their network except via Ashford. By August 1836, the rival [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] (LCDR) made its own proposal to serve Thanet.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=243}} Planning for the line stalled for a while, but by 1840 the SER realised that rival railways were making serious proposals for lines to Thanet.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=244}} After the LCDR's line reached Dover on 22 July 1861, there was serious competition between the two companies for continental port traffic.{{sfn|Grant|2017|p=520}}\n\nConstruction on the line began in September 1884. The SER were not convinced the railway would be a success, and so built it as single track, with space to add an additional track if necessary, and crossed roads at level in several places, including [[Wye, Kent|Wye]], [[Chartham]] and [[Sturry]]. The line ran through [[Minster, Kent|Minster]] to Ramsgate, then doubled back on a branch line to {{rws|Margate Sands}}, which required trains reversing. The overall planned cost was \u00a3385,339.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=244}}\n\nThe line opened as far as Canterbury on 6 February 1846.{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=53}} Intermediate stations were not immediately provided, but opened soon afterwards; [[Wye railway station]] was open by April 1846. A station was planned at [[Godmersham]] but then cancelled. The extension to Ramsgate opened on 13 April, with stations at {{rws|Grove Ferry}}, Minster and Ramsgate. The SER hoped by building the line to Ramsgate, it would be able to run [[boat train]] services to [[Ostend]].{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=245}} The Margate branch was delayed and finally opened on 1 December 1846.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=246}} An intermediate station at Sturry opened on 22 April 1847.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=246}}\n\nThe goods and cattle facilities at Ramsgate made the line popular for transporting these, and they were extended in 1895. An additional siding was added at Wye in 1895 to serve racing traffic.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=251}}\n\nThe rivalry between the SER and LDCR almost bankrupted both companies, and consequently they formed a joined management committee, known as the [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]] (SECR), in 1899.{{sfn|Grant|2017|p=520}} This then became part of the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]] (SR) as part of the grouping under the [[Railways Act 1921]]. In 1924, a {{convert|1.5|miles|adj=on}} extension began construction between the former SER line at Ramsgate and the former LCDR line at {{rws|Dumpton Park}}. This opened on 2 July 1926. At the same time, the former SER branch to Margate Sands closed to passengers, as did the stations at {{rws|Ramsgate Town}} and {{rws|Ramsgate Harbour}}. The Margate Sands branch line survived as a goods depot until November 1976, when it was closed completely.{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2007|p=52-53,66}}\n\nThe line was electrified in 1961 under the [[British Railways|BR]] [[1955 Modernisation Plan]].{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2007|p=53}} Grove Ferry station closed on 3 January 1966.{{sfn|McCarthy|McCarthy|2007|p=123}}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\nOn 11 August 1858, an excursion train was derailed near {{rws|Chilham}}. Three people were killed.<ref name=Kidner>{{cite book | first = R. W.| last = Kidner| year = 1977 |origyear=1963 | title = The South Eastern and Chatham Railway | publisher = The Oakwood Press| location = Tarrant Hinton | isbn = | page=48 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 January 1877, a major storm hit Kent, causing damage along the line. The roof at Canterbury West was damaged, and a timber bridge across the line blew down. The bridge was replaced three months later by a subway.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=250}}\n\nOn 9 October 1894, an early morning goods train carrying hop pickers from Ashford to Canterbury West collided with a horse and cart on a level crossing close to Horton Chapel Farm. Five people were killed immediately, and two later died from their injuries. The SER denied responsibility and blamed the cart driver who did not check to see if a train was coming.{{sfn|Gray|1990|p=251}}\n\nOn 15 July 1970, an [[electric multiple unit]] was in collision with a [[lorry]] on an [[level crossing|occupation crossing]] between {{rws|Chartham}} and Chilham due to an error by the crossing keeper. The driver of the lorry and the guard of the train were killed.<ref name=Glover>{{cite book |title=Southern Electric |first=John |last=Glover |publisher=Ian Allan |location=Hersham |year=2001 |page=142 |isbn=0 7110 2807 9}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 July 2015, electric multiple unit [[British Rail Class 375|375 703]] was in collision with a herd of [[cattle]] on the line at Chilham and was derailed. There were no injuries amongst the 70 passengers.<ref name=BBC33671351>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-33671351 |title=Train derailed after hitting cows on line in Kent |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=KO40716>{{cite web |url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/ashford/news/train-derailed-after-hitting-cattle-40716/ |title=Southeastern Train travelling between Chilham and Wye derails after hitting cattle |publisher=Kent Messenger Group |work=Kent Online |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref> The line was closed until 30 July.<ref name=BBC33692912>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-33692912 |title=Kent line closed by cows-on-line derailment to reopen |publisher=BBC News Online |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{butt-stations}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grant|first=Donald|title=Directory of the Railway Companies of Great Britain|publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd|year=2017|isbn=978-1-788-03768-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gray|first=Adrian|title=South Eastern Railway|publisher=Middleton Press|year=1990|isbn=978-0-906520-85-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=McCarthy|first=Colin|last2=McCarthy|first2=David|title=Railway of Britain : Kent and Sussex|